<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-11-20T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-11-20T05:00:00-05:00" n="634" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d634">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">711.933/171: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-11-20T18:00:00+08:00">November 20, 1929—6
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received November 21—2:55 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>1014. My 1009, November 19, 6 p.m., last paragraph. Following from
                            American Consul at Nanking: <pb facs="0770" n="626" xml:id="pg_626"/>
                            <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“November 19, 12 p.m. Wang informed me tonight that, knowing that
                                    the American Minister was leaving Peiping, he had telegraphed
                                    his views, in reply to the American extraterritoriality note of
                                    November 1st, to Chinese Minister in Washington for
                                    communication to Department of State.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>